---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<ProjectLayout
  title="Cycling Infrastructure & Shared E-Scooter Behaviour"
  year="2025"
  section="Data Science & Analysis"
  category="Master's Thesis · Tel Aviv University"
  tools={['Python', 'GeoPandas', 'OSMnx', 'Map Matching', 'Statistical Analysis', 'QGIS']}
>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Background</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        Shared dockless e-scooters became a fixture of urban mobility within a few years — but how the
        built environment, and cycling infrastructure especially, shapes the way people actually ride
        and park them is still an open question. This MSc thesis investigated that relationship in
        Tel Aviv-Yafo using roughly <strong>1 million trips and 2 million vehicle status transitions</strong>
        recorded in July 2023, asking whether riders take the shortest route home or go out of their
        way to stay near bike lanes — and whether that preference shows up in parking and demand
        patterns too.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Maps — Chosen Route vs. Shortest Path</h2>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/thesis-route-vs-shortest-path.jpg`}
      alt="Map comparing a rider's chosen route along the Tel Aviv coastal cycling lane (3,036m, green) against the shortest possible path (2,105m, red)"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      A rider heading south chose a 3,036m route along the coastal cycling lane (green, dotted = bike lanes)
      over a 2,105m shortest path (red) — adding roughly 45% extra distance to stay on the dedicated lane.
    </p>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/thesis-route-vs-shortest-path-2.jpg`}
      alt="Map comparing a rider's chosen route that follows a bike lane (2,030m, green) against the shorter direct path (1,494m, red)"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      A second example: the chosen route (green, 2,030m) tracks a bike lane axis for most of its length,
      while the shortest path (red, 1,494m) cuts directly through the street grid.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Methodology</h2>
    <ul class="proj-list">
      <li>Cleaned and prepared two raw <strong>MDS-format</strong> datasets — anonymised trip records and vehicle status-change logs — sourced from operators' shared-mobility feeds.</li>
      <li><strong>Map-matched</strong> each recorded route onto the <strong>OpenStreetMap</strong> network with <strong>OSMnx</strong> and computed its shortest-path alternative, measuring exactly how much (and where) riders deviated from the most direct way.</li>
      <li>Overlaid the city's ~175 km of mapped bike lanes onto both chosen and shortest-path routes to test whether riders' actual paths ran along cycling infrastructure more than the optimal path would.</li>
      <li>Spatially joined vehicle parking events to the bike-lane network, neighbourhoods and traffic zones with <strong>GeoPandas</strong>, then ran statistical tests to check whether supply and demand cluster near cycling infrastructure more than chance would predict.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Results</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        Riders extended their routes by about <strong>9% beyond the shortest path</strong> on average —
        and longer trips saw bigger detours. Chosen routes consistently carried a higher share of
        cycling infrastructure than the shortest-path alternative would, and parking events clustered
        near bike lanes at <strong>roughly twice the rate</strong> random chance would produce. A
        closer look showed that how well a bike lane connects to a destination matters: well-connected
        lanes drew tight vehicle clusters, while harder-to-reach lanes saw riders peel off toward the
        destination itself.
      </p>
    </div>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/thesis-bike-share-chosen-vs-shortest.png`}
      alt="Line chart titled 'Share of links with a bike path' comparing the chosen route (blue, 50–63%) against the shortest path (green, 38–45%) across route-length bands from under 1km to over 5km"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      Across every route-length band, the chosen route (blue) ran along bike-path links far more often than the
      shortest-path alternative (green) would — a gap of roughly 12–19 percentage points that widens with trip length.
    </p>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/thesis-detour-ratio-histogram.png`}
      alt="Histogram of the ratio between chosen-route length and shortest-path length, sharply peaked just above 1.0 with a labelled mean of 1.09"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      Distribution of chosen-route length divided by shortest-path length: the vast majority of trips cluster just
      above a ratio of 1.0, with a mean of 1.09 — the numerical backbone of the "~9% longer than necessary" finding above.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Thesis Document</h2>
    <p class="proj-body">
      The full thesis — including the complete literature review, methodology, data tables and discussion —
      is available to download below.
    </p>
    <a class="proj-download" href={`${base}/thesis.pdf`} download>
      <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
        <path d="M6 1v7M3.5 5.5L6 8l2.5-2.5M1 10h10" stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
      </svg>
      Download Thesis (PDF)
    </a>
  </section>

</ProjectLayout>

<style>
  :global(.proj-list) {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 10px;
    max-width: 68ch;
  }
  :global(.proj-list li) {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: #2A2A2A;
    padding-left: 1.2em;
    position: relative;
  }
  :global(.proj-list li::before) {
    content: '—';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: #3D5E35;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .proj-download {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 8px;
    margin-top: 16px;
    padding: 10px 20px;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: #F0EAE0;
    background: #3D5E35;
    border-radius: 4px;
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: background 0.15s;
    width: fit-content;
  }
  .proj-download:hover { background: #2E4828; }
</style>
